{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619203"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16544"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.14,0.11,0,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9235"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10300"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe basal ganglia are a group of subcortical nuclei that play a crucial role in motor control. They influence movement through two primary pathways: the direct pathway and the indirect pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of dopamine in basal ganglia function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["In the direct pathway dopamine acts in an excitatory manner on D1 receptors in the striatum","In the direct pathway dopamine acts in an inhibitory manner on D1 receptors in the striatum","In the indirect pathway dopamine acts in an excitatory manner on D2 receptors in the striatum","In both pathways dopamine has an inhibitory action on D1 receptors","In both pathways dopamine has an excitatory action on D2 receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the basal ganglia, it is correct that \u003Cstrong\u003Ein the direct pathway dopamine acts in an excitatory manner on D1 receptors in the striatum\u003C/strong\u003E. The direct pathway is activated to promote movement. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn the direct pathway dopamine acts in an inhibitory manner on D1 receptors in the striatum\u003C/strong\u003E - D1 receptor activation is excitatory, not inhibitory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn the indirect pathway dopamine acts in an excitatory manner on D2 receptors in the striatum\u003C/strong\u003E - D2 receptor activation is inhibitory within the indirect pathway, leading to movement inhibition. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn both pathways dopamine has an inhibitory action on D1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Only the direct pathway uses D1 receptors, and they are excitatory\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn both pathways dopamine has an excitatory action on D2 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - D2 receptors are inhibitory and only present on the indirect pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combined effect of dopamine acting in an excitatory manner in the direct pathway via D1 receptors and an inhibitory manner in the indirect pathway via D2 receptors promotes smooth, coordinated movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dopamine has an excitatory effect at D1 receptors in the the direct pathway which promotes movement","Dopamine has an inhibitory effect at D2 receptors in the indirect pathway to suppress movement","The balance of the direct and indirect pathways modulates overall movement control"],"references":["Rice ME, Patel JC, Cragg SJ. Dopamine release in the basal ganglia. Neuroscience. 2011 Dec 15;198:112-37. doi: 10.1016/j.neuroscience.2011.08.066. Epub 2011 Sep 14. PMID: 21939738; PMCID: PMC3357127.","Simonyan K. Recent advances in understanding the role of the basal ganglia. F1000Res. 2019 Jan 30;8:F1000 Faculty Rev-122. doi: 10.12688/f1000research.16524.1. PMID: 30755797; PMCID: PMC6354324.","Lanciego JL, Luquin N, Obeso JA. Functional neuroanatomy of the basal ganglia. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012 Dec 1;2(12):a009621. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a009621. PMID: 23071379; PMCID: PMC3543080."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61443"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T14:41:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:41:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9235"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75941"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"